<DOC><DOCNO> AP900507-0206 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-90 0724EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-07 0835</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0873</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The nation's unemployment rate climbed inApril to 5.4 percent, its highest level in more than a year, thegovernment said.   Friday's report triggered a huge rally in bond prices that sentinterest rates skidding as analysts said the figures indicated theeconomy could slip into recession.   There was little growth in the number of U.S. jobs for thesecond straight month, and the total would have declined if not forthe hiring of temporary census workers.</TEXT><DATELINE>NAPA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Trade ministers representing the largestindustrial countries reported they had failed to resolve majordisputes blocking an ambitious effort to overhaul the globaltrading system.   Speaking at the end of a three-day negotiating session,officials of the United States, Japan, the 12-nation EuropeanCommunity and Canada said Friday that sharp differences stillremained over such issues as a U.S. demand for the elimination ofcostly agricultural barriers.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   In an attempt to avoid a ``cripplingnationwide rail strike,'' President Bush named an emergency boardto help settle bargaining disputes between 11 unions and most ofthe nation's major railroads.   Rising health care costs had been a major holdup in contractnegotiations, which had been going on for two years. Nearly 300,000trackmen, engineers, signalmen and other railroad workers at about15 of the nation's largest freight railroads are affected.   Bush's move Friday was hailed by organized labor as a sign thatthe administration is concerned about workers' medical coverage.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Congressional testimony by convicted junk bondfinancier Michael Milken before he is sentenced could complicatethe securities fraud case, the nation's top securities regulatorsaid.   Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman Richard C. Breedensaid Friday the commission will ``try to work with Congress to makesure they understand the status of the case as they consider whathearings they wish to have and when they want to have them.''   The oversight and investigations subcommittee of the HouseEnergy and Commerce Committee voted unanimously Tuesday to subpoenaMilken, who pleaded guilty to six felonies and agreed to pay $600million in penalties last month.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Departing savings and loan cleanup boss L.William Seidman said that ``real pain'' is yet to come in thebailout and urged patience with his successor.   Seidman told a House Banking Committee task force on the Sandamp;Lbailout Friday that rising interest rates and falling propertyvalues indicate ``the costs will exceed those originallyestimated.''   At Seidman's suggestion, President Bush is turning to WilliamTaylor, the Federal Reserve Board's director of bank supervision,to take over the position.</TEXT><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Greyhound Lines Inc. said it lost $55.8 million inthe first quarter and would miss millions of dollars in paymentsdue in coming weeks because of problems related to a 2-month-oldstrike by bus drivers.   The disclosures Friday were the first indication since thestrike of the financial condition at Greyhound, which operates thethe only nationwide bus system. Greyhound in large part blamed $20million in unanticipated expenses to cope with strike-relatedviolence.</TEXT><DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Donald Trump's three casinos arebeing investigated in a financial review that state officials saidwas routine and had nothing to do with disgruntled contractors orthe Manhattan developer's desire to sell some assets.   Anthony J. Parrillo, director of the state Division of GamingEnforcement, said Friday the review has been under way for twomonths.   Parrillo said it was coincidental that the review coincided withstatements from Trump last week that he was considering sellingsome of his holdings, which include Manhattan real estate and theTrump Shuttle airline.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Whittle Communications said it is consolidatingits media properties designed for schools into one division andnamed a former executive of Turner Broadcasting Systems Inc. tohead the new unit.   The Knoxville, Tenn.-based media company said Friday it expectsits new Whittle Educational Network division to generate annualrevenue of $125 million by 1991, or about 40 percent of thecompany's expected revenue of more than $300 million by 1991.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two key directors of the troubled advertising andconsulting giant Saatchi andamp; Saatchi Co. PLC have resigned.   Roy Warman and Terry Bannister served as joint chief operatingofficers of Saatchi's communications division with responsibilityfor worldwide advertising operations. Saatchi's deputy chairmanJeremy Sinclair was named Friday to replace them.   Saatchi is trying to sell the consulting business.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices staged a broad advance Friday, as the Dow Jonesaverage of 30 industrials rose 14.19 to 2,710.36, stretching itsweekly gain to 65.31 points.   Bond prices staged a furious rally that sent interest ratessharply lower.   The dollar fell against every major currencies except theJapanese yen.   Sugar futures prices plunged; cocoa futures fell sharply; copperfutures retreated; precious metals were mostly lower; oil futuresadvanced; grains and soybeans were mixed; and livestock and meatfutures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>